Polish Stocks: Kulczyk Oil, Bank Pekao, Warsaw Exchange Shares

-- B y   P a w e l   K o z l o w s k i
-- 
2011-12-01T16:47:28Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-01/polish-stocks-kghm-polska-lotos-orlen-warsaw-exchange-move.html
Poland ’s  WIG20 Index (WIG20)  declined 23.04
points, or 1 percent, to 2,265.03 at the close in Warsaw, after
posting the biggest daily gain in 18 months yesterday.  The following are among the most active stocks on the
Warsaw Stock Exchange today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Kulczyk Oil Ventures Inc. (KOV)  , controlled by Polish
billionaire Jan Kulczyk, rose 5.2 percent to 1.42 zloty, closing
at a two-week high. A group including Kulczyk Oil completed the
purchase of a 45 percent stake in the OML 42 oil extraction
project in  Nigeria  for $585 million, the company said in a
regulatory statement.  Bank Pekao SA (PEO)  , controlled by UniCredit SpA, lost
2.4 percent to 142.8 zloty, the steepest drop in two weeks.
Poland’s second-largest bank was cut to “neutral” from
“outperform” at Credit Suisse Group AG.  Warsaw Stock Exchange (GPW)   declined 2.1 percent to 38.1
zloty. The operator of central Europe’s biggest equity market
had its share-price estimate cut to 43 zloty from 46 zloty at
JPMorgan Chase & Co.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Pawel Kozlowski in Warsaw 
